body:
A slightly modified version of Example 2 from [here](https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/2094-nll.html#reborrow-constraints) fails:
```rust
fn main() {
    let foo: &mut i32       = &mut 22;
    let mut r_a: &&mut i32  = & foo;
    let r_b: &mut &&mut i32 = &mut r_a;
    let r_c: &&mut i32      = & **r_b;

    // What is considered borrowed here?
    *r_b = &&mut 0;

    println!("{}", r_c);
}
```
with the following error:
```
error[E0716]: temporary value dropped while borrowed
  --> src/main.rs:8:13
   |
8  |     *r_b = &&mut 0;
   |             ^^^^^^- temporary value is freed at the end of this statement
   |             |
   |             creates a temporary which is freed while still in use
9  | 
10 |     println!("{}", r_c);
   |                    --- borrow later used here
   |
   = note: consider using a `let` binding to create a longer lived value
```
However, clearly `r_c` does not reborrow from `r_a` nor from `r_b`. Therefore, using it at the end should not affect either of these, but as we can see this is not the case. If one comments out the `println!` on line 10, then compilation succeeds as expected. Playground link [here](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=aed343ce90ea76a5728ef67885f5a6b4)
